  <his_func>&lt;p&gt;The secretary supported the Governor in his work. He filed copies of transmitted missives and related attachments of the Governor, the so-called "Overgezonden brieven en papieren (O.B.P.)". He received documents from the colony itself (petitions, for example) and from The Netherlands.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;From 1717 there were two secretaries: one who assisted the Council of Policy and a second to assist the Council of Civil Justice. Until 1828 the secretaries also took notarial deeds, except deeds of conveyance and mortgage (before the Council of Policy). The government secretary supplied the administrative support of the Colonial Council (1833-1845). Since 1833 the government secretary took over the function of keeping control with respect to the treatment of the indigenous peoples, including slaves.&lt;/p&gt;</his_func>
